name: Titi's Cranberry Walnut Pumpkin Bread Cake
description: My Titi (auntie in Spanish) handed me down this recipe after I had this cake at her house during a Thanksgiving dinner, and I just to make it for my family at home. It's a great recipe that even my daughter loves! Now this cake makes its way onto my table every Thanksgiving dinner and everyone loves it. I even have a few copies of the recipe because someone always asks for it! Serve with a dollop of Cool Whip®.

recipeInstructions.text: Preheat oven to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C). Grease a 9 1/2-inch fluted cake pan (such as Bundt®).
Whisk flour, baking powder, pumpkin pie spice, and salt together in a bowl.

Beat sugar, pumpkin, vegetable oil, and eggs together in a bowl until smooth. Slowly beat flour mixture into pumpkin mixture until batter is smooth. Fold in cranberries and walnuts. Pour into prepared cake pan.
Bake in the preheated oven until a toothpick inserted in the center of the cake comes out clean, about 35 minutes.

aggregateRating.itemReviewed: Titi's Cranberry Walnut Pumpkin Bread Cake

review.reviewBody: I followed the recipe exactly as it is and let me tell you it was a great hit! Everyone loved it even the little ones that swore they would never eat pumpkin in any way! Took half of it to the office and sprinkled it with powdered sugar everyone was asking me to make them some. It truly is delicious and easy to make. I used pumpkin cooked in cinnamon like it is suggested. I tried it with canned pumpkin but it just doesn't taste the same. Its better with fresh pumpkin and if its baked it takes out a lot of the moisture it takes from boiling it. I like to boil mine with cinnamon either way I just let it sit in a strainer and come back to it every now and then to stir and pat dry with a paper towel any excess water that comes out of it. I have made it several times already and it gets rave reviews everywhere I take it! Love it!

Nice flavor and moist! I don't like a lot of sweets so I cut the sugar in half and used Truvia; I also used 1/4 cup oil and 1/4 cup applesauce. I used canned pumpkin and I think the batter might have been a little too thick so perhaps I should have used 1/2 cup oil. It still came out great and was easy to throw together for a last minute dessert. thanks for the recipe

Wow!! It's hard to impress me; but this recipe is amazing! The longer it sits, the more intense the flavor becomes! I added one of those tiny bottles of Cracker Barrel maple syrup for an extra taste of fall. I highly recommend this recipe, especially if you love all things pumpkin!
